<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-462-808  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 462 808.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Telecommunications  July 1989 v23 n7 p42(3).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>What users should know about computer viruses. (includes relatedarticle on prevention and cures for viruses)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Hawkins, Corinne C.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Computer viruses spread from computer to computer through sharedfloppy disks, telecommunication systems or electronic bulletinboards.andP;  ARPAnet Data Virus caused a crisis in 1980 when messagesfrom node to node could not be thrown out; they collected, causingthe computer system to come to a halt.andP;  The Brain Virus contains amessage, 'Welcome to the dungeon...' and offers users an addressand phone number to a company called Brain Computer Services, butthere is no known cure for the virus.andP;  MacInVirus, that isdisguised as a resource and posted to CompuServe in a HyperCard,is easily defeated with a few lines of assembly code and a coupleof pages of Pascal.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Computer virusesUser AssistanceNetwork ManagementDefinitionsTelecommunications.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>